Here is a way to generate the sequence of pairs: For each integer $i\leq n$, enumerate the integers $j<i$, and for each such $i$ and $j$ generate the pair $(i, j)$. In terms of sequence operations, we map along the sequence (enumerate-interval 1 n)enumerate_interval(1, n). For each $i$ in this sequence, we map along the sequence (enumerate-interval 1 (- i 1))enumerate_interval(1, i-1). For each $j$ in this latter sequence, we generate the pair (list i j)list(i, j). This gives us a sequence of pairs for each $i$. Combining all the sequences for all the $i$ (by accumulating with appendappend) produces the required sequence of pairs:Were representing a pair here as a list of two elements rather than as a Lisp pairan ordinary pair. Thus, the pair $(i, j)$ is represented as (list i j)list(i, j), not (cons i j)pair(i, j).
enumerate_interval_n
const n = 6;
enumerate_interval enumerate_interval_n
;; replace n below by the desired number (accumulate append nil (map (lambda (i) (map (lambda (j) (list i j)) (enumerate-interval 1 (- i 1)))) (enumerate-interval 1 n)))
accumulate(append, null, map(i => map(j => list(i, j), enumerate_interval(1, i-1)), enumerate_interval(1, n)));

